00:07.777 --> 00:10.582
Okay, what are the good parts of House Bill 72? 
Well, we've hit on a number of them. The increase in

00:13.827 --> 00:17.433
teacher salaries was essential. I mean, the 
salary before the bill was $11,100, and 70% of the

00:17.453 --> 00:33.801
districts we had ever studied showed that 70% of 
the districts 40 years ago did not add more than 10%

00:17.453 --> 00:33.801
to that base.

00:36.633 --> 00:41.598
Well, in terms of attracting and keeping big 
people, it was not competitive. The 15-2 isn't

00:41.638 --> 00:43.900
really competitive yet. I mean, with the bonuses 
in the career ladder, it could be, but those are

00:43.920 --> 01:04.739
going to have to be increased because if you 
compare the salaries of people who have graduated

00:43.920 --> 01:04.739
from Texas A&M with a four-year degree, right, in 
other fields such as business and engineering and

00:43.920 --> 01:04.739
these other fields, the 15-2 isn't competitive. 
You're going to have to go beyond that. I'd like to

01:06.535 --> 01:21.415
see us move more toward a career ladder with a 
12-month employment for some teachers where they

01:06.535 --> 01:21.415
can work with tutoring programs in the summer, 
special programs for the gifted, like the program

01:06.535 --> 01:21.415
they have up in Garland. They have a program called 
Academic Coaches where they work in the summer.

01:26.462 --> 01:35.935
And instead of just having them coach, like the 
coaches are hired to coach the football in the

01:26.462 --> 01:35.935
summer, these people are hired to coach kids who 
are gifted kids or kids with special problems, and

01:36.320 --> 01:47.175
move toward a system where we have third and fourth 
level career ladder teachers on a 10-month

01:36.320 --> 01:47.175
assignment, a 12-month assignment. Not 
necessarily teaching in regular class, but

01:47.195 --> 02:05.820
running training programs for other teachers in 
the summer, setting up programs where you can have

01:47.195 --> 02:05.820
the beginning teachers of the previous year come 
back in that summer for extra help from moving into

01:47.195 --> 02:05.820
the second year, not treat the beginners as if 
they're experienced people, Every other

02:05.918 --> 02:11.984
profession has an induction program for 
beginning teachers. And they have a mentor

02:12.004 --> 02:16.909
working with them through their first year of 
teaching. And then they work with them in their

02:16.929 --> 02:20.212
second year. And those are the kinds of things that 
I think are going to be essential. So the salary

02:23.856 --> 02:31.523
thing and the structure for career ladders, if we 
can work it out, would be one of the best things to

02:23.856 --> 02:31.523
ever happen. The scholarship programs have to be 
expanded. The research and development

02:36.428 --> 02:40.113
component that's in there, the uses of the new 
technology. See, part of the solution to the

02:40.133 --> 02:45.340
teacher shortage is not to try to keep doing what 
we're doing. It's to use the talent you've got

02:45.860 --> 02:50.947
better in a differentiating way. And have some of 
the models, like talk to us. We have the master

02:53.971 --> 02:58.256
teacher, the two regular teachers, and two 
interns. Take 100 students. And you match your

03:01.083 --> 03:16.521
five people, one with a math background, one with a 
science background, one with an English

03:01.083 --> 03:16.521
background, one with a social studies 
background, and a backup person to work with the

03:01.083 --> 03:16.521
computers and the technology, working as a team 
with those 100 students. And then you utilize the

03:16.541 --> 03:24.391
talents of the people in different ways with those 
100 students. Instead of organizing the school

03:24.411 --> 03:30.398
around each 50-minute period, we've done 50 
minutes of math, 50 minutes of media, 50 minutes in

03:30.850 --> 03:36.217
science, 50 minutes in the gym, 50 minutes in 
foreign language. I mean, it's boring. Just more

03:37.980 --> 03:42.025
